Regenerative vs. Traditional Agriculture

Regenerative agriculture applies methods that boost soil health and biodiversity. Traditional agriculture practices, on the other hand, are often harmful to the soil, water, and biodiversity.


Why Regenerative Agriculture Matters

Regenerative agriculture practices enhance productivity and farmer resilience, mitigate climate change, and ensure sustainable livelihoods, biodiversity, and ecosystem services.


Current Agriculture Status at Hamilton College

Currently, Hamilton College has a few regenerative agriculture projects. However, there is no organized group to promote and implement regenerative agriculture practices or projects.


Benefits of Regenerative Agriculture Practices


Improved Soil Health


Regenerative agriculture practices improve soil health, which benefits crop yields, water retention, erosion control, and carbon sequestration.

Enhanced Biodiversity


Regenerative agriculture restores and enhances biodiversity, which improves ecosystem services such as pollination, pest control, and soil nutrient cycling.

Increased Farmer Resilience

Regenerative agriculture practices increase farmer resilience by boosting their capacity to adapt to volatile weather conditions, pests, and market demands.

The Case for a Sustainable Agriculture Club at Hamilton College


Curriculum Integration


A sustainable agriculture club can promote regenerative agriculture curriculum, research opportunities, internships, and collaborations with NGOs and other academic institutions.


1


Bridging the Gap


A sustainable agriculture club can help bridge the gap between the Hamilton College community and sustainable food systems by promoting regenerative agriculture practices and initiatives.

2 3


Community Engagement


A sustainable agriculture club can promote student engagement by fostering on-campus regenerative agriculture programs.


Club Activities for Year 1, Year 2, and Year 3


Year 1

Establish a regenerative agriculture demonstration site on campus.

Organize a regenerative agriculture film series and workshops.

Invite guest lectures from regenerative agriculture experts.

Year 2

Design and implement community-supported agriculture (CSA) program with support from local farmers.

Offer summer regenerative agriculture internships for students in collaboration with local organizations.

Year 3

Organize regenerative agriculture symposium with participation from regional and international regenerative agriculture experts.

Expand CSA program and establish a regenerative agriculture research hub.
